    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{r}{r+4}} = {3} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-6\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{r+4}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r}{r+4}} \amp = {3} \\
   {\frac{r}{r+4}} \cdot ({r+4}) \amp = {3} \cdot ({r+4}) \\
   r \amp = 3r+12 \\
   r \mathbf{-3r} \amp = 3r+12 \mathbf{-3r} \\
   -2r \amp = 12 \\
   \frac{-2r}{-2} \amp = \frac{12}{-2} \\
   r \amp = -6
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>r+4 \ne 0</m>, or <m>r \ne -4</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>r = -6</m>.</p>
</solution>
